      <body>
         <head type="date">
            <date when="1803-12-31">December 31, 1803</date>
         </head>
         <div type="entry" xml:id="lc.jrn.1803-12-31.01" n="lc.geo.1803-12-31.01">
            <sp who="wc">
               <speaker>Clark</speaker>
               <ab>
                  <date/>
               </ab>
               <p>
Saty, 31st of Decr    I Issued certain [orders?] &amp; prohibited a Certain [<hi rend="italic">blank</hi>] <name type="person" key="Ramey, Matthew or William">Ramey</name>
                  <ref target="n03123101" n="1"/> from Selling Liquer to the Party, Several things Killed to day. <name type="person" key="Colter, John">Colter</name> [<name type="person" key="Ordway, John">Oddawey</name>?]<ref target="n03123102" n="2"/>
                  <name type="person" key="Willard, Alexander">Willard</name>
                  <name type="person" key="Leakens">Leakens</name>
                  <ref target="n03123103" n="3"/>
                  <name type="person" key="Hall, Hugh">Hall</name> &amp; <name type="person" key="Collins, John">Collins</name> Drunk.    began to snow at Dark and Continued untill 9 oClock    Cloudy to day<ref target="n03123104" n="4"/>
               </p>
            </sp>
         </div>
      </body>
      <back>
         <div type="notes">
            <note xml:id="n03123101" n="1">
               <name type="person" key="Ramey, Matthew">Matthew Ramey</name> took up residence in the <name type="place" key="Saint Louis, Mo.">St. Louis</name> district in 1803; <name type="person" key="Ramy, William">William Ramy</name> signed a memorial to the president from the <name type="place" key="Saint Charles, Mo.">St. Charles</name> district in 1806. Osgood (FN), 11 n. 8.</note>
            <note xml:id="n03123102" n="2">Osgood interprets this illegible word as "<name type="person" key="Ordway, John">Oddawey</name>," but <name type="person" key="Ordway, John">Sergeant Ordway</name> was absent from camp from December 30 to January 2. The word may be "souber" written over another word, in which case <name type="person" key="Willard, Alexander">Willard</name>, <name type="person" key="Leakens">Leakens</name>, <name type="person" key="Hall, Hugh">Hall</name> and <name type="person" key="Collins, John">Collins</name> were the only drunken men. Ibid., 11.</note>
           <note xml:id="n03123103" n="3">For <name type="person" key="Leakens">Leakens</name> (possibly "<name type="person" key="Leakens">Seakens</name>"), see below, <ref n="lc.jrn.1804-02-04" type="related">February 4, 1804</ref>, concerning his discharge. Nothing else is known of him.</note>
            <note xml:id="n03123104" n="4">Below this entry and written crossways are the following figures:<lb/>
